Project Overview

PartsSource is deploying the Atlas Renewal Agent to automate and scale renewal engagement across the REMI long-tail segment of approximately 1,500 accounts with policies under $20k. The current process reaches customers only 30–60 days before renewal, leaving no time to address service issues, pricing concerns, or contact changes. The goal is to replicate the structured renewal methodology used for the enterprise segment at the scale the long tail requires.

 

Current State

Today, the REMI renewal process is compressed into a 60–30 day pre-renewal window, driven by two procurement workflows:

PO-based customers: Outreach triggered 60 days before renewal. The team sends the renewal agreement by email with follow-up every 2–3 weeks, including phone calls and contact searches when customers are unresponsive.

Auto-renew customers: Notification sent 30 days before renewal. Less active engagement  the renewal registers automatically unless the customer declines.

“Renewal Queen” generates 5 email template variants based on: PO requirement, pricing changes (if over 10–15%), vendor restrictions, non-renewal items, and auto-renewal status.



Renewal quote workflow: Pricing generates quote in Polaris, which moves into a staging Access database. Account Services processes these weekly. Customer Service then receives a notification email and updates the Salesforce opportunity, then uses the Renewal Queen to generate the customer email. Quotes are arriving very late (3 weeks to 1 month before effective date) due to upstream bottlenecks.

The PO/auto-renew flag is captured as a checkbox field in Polaris. Prior to October 2024, the REMI customer service team was just 3 people managing ~3,400 renewals per year. The customer service team works exclusively in Salesforce (REMI instance), they have no access to Gainsight today. Emails are manually uploaded to the Salesforce file section for record-keeping (drag-and-drop, not an activity timeline feed). The team also uses Op360 (an outside vendor) to assist with some manual renewal processes.

 

Key current-state metrics:

On-time renewal rate (2025): ~55% across the full portfolio.  Target 75%

Controllable churn: ~48% of annual churn is controllable, driven by late or missed engagement; 52% uncontrollable (OEM pricing gaps, federal/state budget cuts)

Renewal volume: ~3,400 policies per year across the full REMI portfolio

Early warning signals: Gut instinct, team collaboration, and spot audits. New situations arise weekly.



 

Value Statement and Priorities



Current operational pain: The REMI renewal team cannot engage ~1,500 long-tail accounts proactively. Outreach begins at T-60 to T-30 instead of the ideal T-180. Prior to late 2024, just 3 people managed ~3,400 renewals; capacity constraints make earlier engagement operationally impossible without automation.



Root cause: Manual processes, a small team, and four disconnected data systems (REMI Salesforce, Polaris, Access database, Gainsight CS) make structured early outreach impossible at scale.



Business consequence: On-time renewal rates sit at ~55% across the full portfolio (target: 70–80%), and GRR is ~80–82% against a target of 85%  representing material retention risk on a $20M long-tail book. 48% of annual churn is controllable.



Future state: Deploy Atlas to run a structured, multi-touch outreach sequence beginning at T-180, following the confirmed 4-stage methodology (Expressed Interest → Solution Scoping → Solution Proposal → Contracting), enabling 100% methodology compliance and freeing the team for higher-value customer work.



Leading indicators: First outreach triggered at T-180 for 100% of REMI long-tail accounts; structured cadence through T-30; escalations categorized and routed to the correct team (Sales, Pricing, Legal, Billing) within defined SLAs.



Lagging outcome: 

Improve GRR on REMI segment from ~80% to 85%

Increase on-time renewal rate from ~55% to 70–80%

Achieve 100% renewal methodology compliance (structured outreach beginning at T-180)

 

Additional priorities:

Transform REMI renewal management to free capacity for high-value customer engagement

Provide sales reps with a visibility dashboard into long-tail renewal conversations  even though reps are not compensated on sub-$20k policies, every dollar retained matters to their account-level growth story



 

Anticipated Challenges

Data fragmentation: Four disconnected systems (REMI Salesforce, Polaris, Access database, Gainsight CS) with no shared unique identifier, unless there is a common Polaris Id. The policy/agreement number in Salesforce is a candidate mapping key to Polaris. MVP may need to use a flat file approach unless otherwise agreed upon. 

Impact: A common identifier is required to guide the agent properly 

Tech transformation dependency: PartsSource is undergoing a tech transformation with messy data spread across multiple systems and timeline is TBD with no committed date. Elana cautioned on 3/19 that building connectors to legacy SF would 'massively expand scope.'; MVP design must minimize future rebuild cost.

Impact: It will be difficult to decide on a proper workflow for the agent without a system of record to write back to. 

Contact data quality: Email addresses and decision-maker contacts may not be current for the long-tail segment, especially for decentralized university and government accounts. Contact data quality: 6–9 duplicate contact versions across systems. Consolidation project underway with no one-to-one mapping (ratios as high as 20:1). Contact IDs will change post-migration.

Impact: The agent may not be able to reach as many accounts as desired without key contacts identified. 

Escalation Routing: The agent will need explicit routing instructions: pricing requests go here, service complaints go there, legal questions go somewhere else.

Impact: Without routing instructions, the agent will not streamline processes and followup across the organization.

Multi-policy account routing: Accounts with policies on both sides of the $20k threshold need routing logic to prevent the agent and a sales rep contacting the same customer simultaneously. Brad flagged this as a priority design decision before pilot launch.

Impact: Without clarity on this, we risk confusing the customer with duplicative outreach.

Shared inbox double-response risk: Agent (potentially) and 3-person CS team both monitoring customerservice@theremigroup.com. 

Impact: Miscommunications or lack of coordination if unresolved.

Day-one pipeline state: When agent launches, customers will be at every stage (T-45, T-30, expired). Agent needs triage logic for mid-sequence entry.



 

 

